{{Multiple issues|
{{Underlinked|date=January 2017}}
{{unreferenced|date=January 2017}}
}}

The '''normalized difference red edge index''' ('''NDRE''') is a [[wikt:metric#Noun|metric]] that can be used to analyse whether images obtained from [[Multispectral image|multi-spectral image]] sensors contain healthy vegetation or not. It is similar to [[Normalized Difference Vegetation Index]] (NDVI) but uses the ratio of Near-Infrared and the edge of Red as follows:

:<math>\mbox{NDRE}=\frac{(\mbox{NIR}-\mbox{RE})}{(\mbox{NIR}+\mbox{RE})}</math>

The red edge is the term used to describe the part of the spectrum centred around 715&nbsp;nm.

==External links==
* [http://aerialagimagery.com/NDRE.html Background on NDRE]
* [https://www.harrisgeospatial.com/docs/narrowbandgreenness.html Chlorophyll Absorption]
*Spectral Reflectance Changes Associated with Autumn Senescence of Aesculus hippocastanum L. and Acer platanoides L. Leaves. Spectral Features and Relation to Chlorophyll Estimation  

